{{Infobox football match | title = 1969 Copa Libertadores Finals | image = | event = [[1969 Copa Libertadores]] | team1 = [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]] | team1association = {{flagicon|URU|size=30px}} | team1score = 0 | team2 = [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes (LP)]] | team2association = {{flagicon|ARG|size=30px}} | team2score = 3 | details = Estudiantes won 3-0 on aggregate. | firstleg = First Leg | team1score1 = 0 | team2score1 = 1 | details1 = | date1 = May 15, 1969 | stadium1 = [[Estadio Centenario]] | city1 = [[Montevideo]] | man_of_the_match1a = | man_of_the_match1atitle = | man_of_the_match1b = | man_of_the_match1btitle = | referee1 = [[Domingo Massaro|Massaro]] ([[Chilean Football Federation|Chile]]) | attendance1 = 65,000 | weather1 = | secondleg = Second Leg | team1score2 = 0 | team2score2 = 2 | details2 = | date2 = May 22, 1969 | stadium2 = [[Estadio Jorge Luis Hirschi|Estudiantes]] | city2 = [[La Plata]] | man_of_the_match2a = | man_of_the_match2atitle = | man_of_the_match2b = | man_of_the_match2btitle = | referee2 = [[Delgado]] ([[Colombian Football Federation|Colombia]]) | attendance2 = 55,000 | weather2 = | previous = [[1968 Copa Libertadores Finals|1968]] | next = [[1970 Copa Libertadores Finals|1970]] }}
The '''1969 Copa Libertadores Finals''' were the two-legged final that decided the winner of the [[1969 Copa Libertadores]], the 10th edition of the [[Copa Libertadores|Copa Libertadores de América]], [[South America]]'s premier international club [[association football|football]] tournament organized by [[CONMEBOL]].
The finals were contested in two-legged home-and-away format between [[Argentine Football Association|Argentine]] team [[Estudiantes de La Plata]] and [[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguayan]] team [[Club Nacional de Football|Nacional]]. The first leg was hosted by Nacional at [[Estadio Centenario]] of [[Montevideo]] on May 15, 1969, while the second leg was played at [[Estadio Jorge Luis Hirschi|Estudiantes Stadium]] in [[La Plata]] on May 22, 1969.
Estudiantes won the series 3-0 on aggregate, winning their 2nd. Copa Libertadores title.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/sacups/copa69.html 1969 Copa Libertadores de América] by Pablo Ciullini, John Beuker, Karel Stokkermans and José Luis Pierrend on RSSSF.com</ref>
