{{Infobox cricket ground | ground_name = Barker's Ground | nickname = | country = England | image = | location = [[Leicester]], [[Leicestershire]] | establishment = 1825 (first recorded match) | seating_capacity = | end1 = | end2 = | year2 = 1843 | club2 = [[Midland Counties cricket team|Midland Counties]] | year1 = 1836, 1842, 1844 & 1846 | club1 = [[North of England cricket team|North]] | date = 25 August | year = 2010 | source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/574.html Ground profile }}
'''Barker's Ground''' was a [[cricket]] ground in [[Leicester]], [[Leicestershire]]. The first recorded match on the ground was in 1825, when Leicester played [[Sheffield Cricket Club|Sheffield]]. The first [[first-class cricket|first-class match]] came in 1836, when the [[North of England cricket team|North]] played the [[South of England cricket team|South]]; the South won by 218 runs, largely due to [[Alfred Mynn]]'s two not out innings.<ref>Firth (1926)</ref> The North used the ground for 4 further first-class matches up to 1846, including the ground's final first-class match between the North and the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]]. [[Midland Counties cricket team|Midland Counties]] played a single first-class match at Barker's Ground against the Marylebone Cricket Club in 1843.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/574_f.html First-Class Matches played on Barker's Ground]</ref> The final recorded match on the ground saw Leicestershire play an [[All-England Eleven]] in 1860.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/574_misc.html Other matches played on Barker's Ground]</ref>
The owner of the ground was "Old Barker", the landlord of the Anchor Inn, Halford Street, who did very well from the gate money. The ground was sited on the east side of Wharf Street, near the Humberstone Road.<ref>Firth, J. R. (1926) ''Highways and Byways in Leicestershire''. London: Macmillan; p. 45</ref>
Following the final recorded match held at Barker's Ground, it was sold for building. Today, the ground would be located along Wharf Street, which is in the centre of Leicester.
